{"id":"1910.08560","submitter":"Alexandros Ziampras","authors":"Alexandros Ziampras, Sareh Ataiee, Wilhelm Kley, Cornelis P.\n  Dullemond, and Cl\\'ement Baruteau","title":"The impact of planet wakes on the location and shape of the water\n  iceline in a protoplanetary disk","comments":"Accepted by Astronomy and Astrophysics (A&A). 15 pages, 15 figures, 2\n  tables","journal-ref":"A&A 633, A29 (2020)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/201936495","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Context: Planets in accretion disks can excite spiral shocks, and---if\nmassive enough---open gaps in their vicinity. Both of these effects can\ninfluence the overall disk thermal structure.\n  Aims: We model planets of different masses and semimajor axes in disks of\nvarious viscosities and accretion rates to examine their impact on disk\nthermodynamics and highlight the mutable, non-axisymmetric nature of icelines\nin systems with massive planets.\n  Methods: We conduct a parameter study using numerical hydrodynamics\nsimulations where we treat viscous heating, thermal cooling and stellar\nirradiation as additional source terms in the energy equation, with some runs\nincluding radiative diffusion. Our parameter space consists of a grid\ncontaining different combinations of planet and disk parameters.\n  Results: Both gap opening and shock heating can displace the iceline, with\nthe effects being amplified for massive planets in optically thick disks. The\ngap region can split an initially hot (T>170 K) disk into a hot inner disk and\na hot ring just outside of the planet's location, while shock heating can\nreshape the originally axisymmetric iceline into water-poor islands along\nspirals. We also find that radiative diffusion does not alter the picture\nsignificantly in this context.\n  Conclusions: Shock heating and gap opening by a planet can effectively heat\nup optically thick disks and in general move and/or reshape the water iceline.\nThis can affect the gap structure and migration torques. It can also produce\nazimuthal features that follow the trajectory of spiral arms, creating hot\nzones, \"islands\" of vapor and ice around spirals which could affect the\naccretion or growth of icy aggregates.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Oct 2019 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-08"}
