{"id":"1910.08648","submitter":"Isaac Polinsky","authors":"Isaac Polinsky and Kyle Martin and William Enck and Michael K. Reiter","title":"n-m-Variant Systems: Adversarial-Resistant Software Rejuvenation for\n  Cloud-Based Web Applications","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Web servers are a popular target for adversaries as they are publicly\naccessible and often vulnerable to compromise. Compromises can go unnoticed for\nmonths, if not years, and recovery often involves a complete system rebuild. In\nthis paper, we propose n-m-Variant Systems, an adversarial-resistant software\nrejuvenation framework for cloud-based web applications. We improve the\nstate-of-the-art by introducing a variable m that provides a knob for\nadministrators to tune an environment to balance resource usage, performance\noverhead, and security guarantees. Using m, security guarantees can be tuned\nfor seconds, minutes, days, or complete resistance. We design and implement an\nn-m-Variant System prototype to protect a Mediawiki PHP application serving\ndynamic content from an external SQL persistent storage. Our performance\nevaluation shows a throughput reduction of 65% for 108 seconds of resistance\nand 83% for 12 days of resistance to sophisticated adversaries, given\nappropriate resource allocation. Furthermore, we use theoretical analysis and\nsimulation to characterize the impact of system parameters on resilience to\nadversaries. Through these efforts, our work demonstrates how properties of\ncloud-based servers can enhance the integrity of Web servers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Oct 2019 22:23:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-22"}
